CSS selectors are patterns used to select the HTML elements you want to style. They can be broadly categorized into five main groups, as described by sources like W3Schools and MDN Web Docs. [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]  
Basic/Simple Selectors
These selectors target elements based on their most fundamental characteristics.

• Element (Type) Selector: Selects all elements of a given HTML tag name (e.g., selects all paragraph elements).
• Class Selector: Selects all elements with a specific attribute. It is denoted by a period () followed by the class name (e.g., selects all elements with ).
• ID Selector: Selects a single, unique element with a specific attribute. It is denoted by a hash () followed by the ID name (e.g., selects the element with ). An ID should only be used once per page.
• Universal Selector: Selects all elements on the page. It is denoted by an asterisk () (e.g., removes default margins from all elements).
• Grouping Selector: Combines multiple selectors into a comma-separated list to apply the same styles to all of them, avoiding redundant code (e.g., applies the same style to all , , and elements). [6, 7, 8, 9, 10, 11, 12]

Combinator Selectors
Combinators are used to select elements based on the relationship between them and other elements in the document tree.

• Descendant Selector: Selects all elements that are a descendant of a specified element, regardless of how deep they are nested. It is denoted by a space between selectors (e.g., selects all elements inside a ).
• Child Selector: Selects elements that are direct children of a specified element. It is denoted by the greater-than sign () (e.g., selects only elements whose immediate parent is a ).
• Adjacent Sibling Selector: Selects an element that is the immediate next sibling of another specified element. It is denoted by a plus sign () (e.g., selects the first element that immediately follows an ).
• General Sibling Selector: Selects all sibling elements that follow a specified element. It is denoted by a tilde () (e.g., selects all elements that follow an , as long as they share the same parent). [8, 13, 14, 15, 16]

Pseudo-class Selectors
Pseudo-classes select elements based on a specific state, condition, or position that is not described in the document tree. They are indicated by a single colon ().

• :hover: Styles an element when the user's mouse cursor is over it (e.g., changes the style of a link when hovered).
• :focus: Styles an element when it has focus (e.g., a form input field).
• :nth-child(): Selects elements based on their position among a group of siblings (e.g., selects the second paragraph).
• :visited: Styles links that the user has already visited (e.g., ). [14, 17, 20]

Pseudo-element Selectors
Pseudo-elements are used to style a specific part of an element or to insert content before or after an element. They are indicated by a double colon ().

• ::before: Inserts generated content before the actual content of an element.
• ::after: Inserts generated content after the actual content of an element.
• ::first-line: Styles the first formatted line of a block-level element.
• ::first-letter: Styles the first letter of a block-level element. [9, 23]

Attribute Selectors
These selectors select elements based on the presence or value of a specific HTML attribute. They are contained within square brackets ().

• [attribute]: Selects all elements that have the specified attribute, regardless of its value (e.g., selects all anchor tags with a attribute).
• [attribute="value"]: Selects elements where the attribute's value matches exactly (e.g., selects all input fields with the type "text").
• [attribute^="value"]: Selects elements whose attribute value begins with a specific substring (e.g., selects links where the starts with "https").
• **[attribute$="value"]:** Selects elements whose attribute value ends with a specific substring (e.g., `a[href$=".pdf"]href` ends with ".pdf").
